<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Evidence to ECC inquiry on low carbon innovation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Will McDowall (LCI0006)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a case for increasing the overall level of funding for low carbon energy R&amp;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D, which is lower as a percentage of GDP than that of many key competitors. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is ambiguity about how government selects priority technology areas. The LCICG core technology areas leave important omissions. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LCICG fills a gap for co-ordination of fundi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng for low carbon R&amp;D. It does not fill a larger gap for co-ordination of low-carbon R&amp;D funding with policies that support deployment of low-carbon technologies. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Will the Government’s current approach towards low carbon innovation help to achieve the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’s legally binding targets at the lowest possible cost?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A strong, stable and long-term carbon price would provide an efficient long-term signal across the economy for investment in low-carbon innovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, leading to the achievement of carbon targets at lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, this economically efficient outcome is in practice not achievable, because a) the long-term credibility of such a carbon price is very difficult—if not impossible—to achieve, since current parliaments cannot bind the hands of future legis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, legally binding targets notwithstanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; b) an international carbon price would be required to embed this price signal throughout all products and services, and c) there are many market and system failures within innovation systems that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prevent eff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> responses to price signals, and which may block low-carbon innovation even where it is economically rational. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Effective innovation policy must engage with that complex reality. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s active approach to innovation policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, set out in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BIS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Innovation and Research Strategy for Growth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is therefore very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as it recognises the complexity of innovation and innovation policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The recent development of industrial strategies in particular represents a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sensible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pragmatic break from years o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f polarised debate between ‘laissez faire’ and ‘picking winners’; it recognises that government is an inevitable player within the innovation system, and that intelligent strategic engagement and support is the best approach. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, there are a number </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of shortcomings to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to low carbon innovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In particular, o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">verall public funding for energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RD&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remains low compared to many competitors. There is a case for increasing the overall level of funding support. In particular, there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is a case for providing more long-term forms of finance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">low-carbon sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does relatively well at attracting venture capital, second only to the US among major economies in terms of clean energy VC per unit GDP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (according to data from Bloomberg Ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w Energy Finance)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; but there is a dearth of longer-term supporting finance for em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erging low-carbon technologies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is also a problem with strategic co-ordination. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The failure to join up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">low carbon R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policy and deployment policy with sufficient credi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bility is undermining the UK’s ability to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attract investment in manufacturing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity for key technologies, such as offshore wind. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The continued uncertainty over mid-term carbon targets (particularly in the power sector) and renewable energy commi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tments will raise costs of ultimately meeting targets, and will reduce the chance of the UK benefitting from the associated manufacturing and export opportunities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Part of the problem is the political challenge of achieving alignment on key issues around d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecarbonisation policy. But a second part of the problem is the lack of a strategic co-ordination mechanism for low-carbon innovation. LCICG, while a welcome development, has not been designed for an overall strategic co-ordination mission, nor has it been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resourced to meet such a mission. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the Government have the right balance of focus between energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a lack of clarity about how government has chosen its priority areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and in particular how LCICG has chosen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">target technology areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Particularly striking is the absence of both aviation and automotive technologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from the LCICG list of target technologies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(with the exception of hydrogen, for which a TINA is yet to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">released). Aviation and automotive sectors both receive innovation support from government, and have well-developed industrial strategies. Recent evidence presented to UCL’s Green Economy Policy Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (to be published in early 2014)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also suggests that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UK has a weaker performance in low-carbon innovation in these two sectors (as measured by patents), than other major economies. Furthermore, the Committee on Climate Change</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> highlighted both aviation and electric vehicle technologies as priority techn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ology areas. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Moreover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, low-carbon innovation should not only address energy technologies. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> broader low-carbon perspective might include agricultural technologies and techniques, and land-u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se management, for example. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly, it might move beyond techn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ologies to support low-carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">business models. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Key carbon-intensive sectors may be better ways of structuring government strategy around low carbon innovation needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and opportunities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The TINA process has been valuable in highlighting the innovation pote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntial of a small number of key technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and technology areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is to be hoped that the process can expand its view of technology areas of relevance, including those that are less well represented in systems modelling tools (either because they are le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ss mature, or because there is disagreement about technology cost estimates). Potentially important options excluded from the current set of TINAS include some that are technically achievable, but which would raise significant governance challenges (e.g. H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in gas networks), and those that are longer term and more speculative (tethered high-altitude wind turbines; direct photocatalysis; various energy harvesting technologies). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What outcomes, if any, are the LCICG likely to achieve? How should its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">forthcoming strategy drive more investment into low carbon innovation, and how should it measure success?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LCICG has been an important development in enabling government to co-ordinate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D spending on low-carbon technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LCICG </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not meet t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he need for strategic co-ordination of low-carbon innovation policy identified by the CCC and others. LCICG’s remit is narrow, focused on improving the co-ordination of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">public spending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This had been missing, and LCICG has been useful in ov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ercoming that lack. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, this focus on spending on technologies is only one part of innovation policy, which requires management and co-ordination not only of government-funded R&amp;D programmes, but also of the demand-side and enabling activities.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rouping that could co-ordinate and strategically develop low-carbon innovation policy might be expected to also have representation from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Government Procurement Service (given evidence that well-designed public procurement policies can sti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mulate ‘mission-driven’ innovation) and from the Green Investment Bank. Similarly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it seems unfortunate that the LCICG does not explicitly aim to co-ordinate R&amp;D funding with efforts to remove market or regulatory barriers to low-carbon technologies, or ef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forts to stimulate markets for low-carbon technologies, such as the various subsidy schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LCICG is not particularly well-resourced, and it faces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> challenges in achieving buy-in from across member organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Both of these factors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are key limitations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on its ability to have a significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">positive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">influence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, even within its current narrow remit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, LCICG has been a positive addition to reduce the lack of co-ordination across low carbon R&amp;D funding agencies. However, there remains </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ar champion for low-carbon innovation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ultimately, the value for money of funding low-carbon technology R&amp;D will depend on how well the government is able foster an innovation system that effectively develops </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and deploys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> low carbon technologies. Focusin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g only on the achievement of technology development from a technology-push perspective will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">generate limited results </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if the efforts are not aligned with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">credible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> long-term energy and carbon policy. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How is the Government maximising opportunities to learn </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">from and partner with international partners within and beyond the EU?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here does not appear to be significant effort from LCICG to link to, or co-ordinate with, the European level, which is a major source of funding for low-carbon R&amp;D. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Building a low-carbon economy – the UK’s innovation challenge. Committee on Climate Change, 2010. </span></p></body></html>